SIMPLE: philosophy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Philosophy
<hw>Phi*los"o*phy</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧*l⟦ocr⟧s"⟦osl⟧*f⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Philosophies</plw>
<pr>(f⟦icr⟧*l⟦ocr⟧s"⟦osl⟧*f⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>philosophie</ets>, F. <ets>philosophie</ets>, L.
<ets>philosophia</ets>, from Gr. <grk>filosofi`a</grk>. See
<er>Philosopher</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Literally, the love of,
inducing the search after, wisdom; in actual usage, the knowledge of
phenomena as explained by, and resolved into, causes and reasons, powers
and laws.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ When applied to any particular department of knowledge,
<xex>philosophy</xex> denotes the general laws or principles under which
all the subordinate phenomena or facts relating to that subject are
comprehended. Thus <ex>philosophy</ex>, when applied to God and the
divine government, is called <xex>theology</xex>; when applied to
material objects, it is called <xex>physics</xex>; when it treats of
man, it is called <xex>anthropology</xex> and <xex>psychology</xex>,
with which are connected <xex>logic</xex> and <xex>ethics</xex>; when it
treats of the necessary conceptions and relations by which
<ex>philosophy</ex> is possible, it is called
<xex>metaphysics</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Philosophy</xex> has been defined: -- the
science of things divine and human, and the causes in which they are
contained; -- the science of effects by their causes; -- the science of
sufficient reasons; -- the science of things possible, inasmuch as they
are possible; -- the science of things evidently deduced from first
principles; -- the science of truths sensible and abstract; -- the
application of reason to its legitimate objects; -- the science of the
relations of all knowledge to the necessary ends of human reason; -- the
science of the original form of the ego, or mental self; -- the science
of science; -- the science of the absolute; -- the science of the
absolute indifference of the ideal and real.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Sir
W. Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A particular philosophical system or theory; the
hypothesis by which particular phenomena are explained.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Books] of Aristotle and his <qex>philosophie</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We shall in vain interpret their words by the notions of our
<qex>philosophy</qex> and the doctrines in our school.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Practical wisdom; calmness of temper and judgment;
equanimity; fortitude; stoicism; <as>as, to meet misfortune with
<ex>philosophy</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then had he spent all his <qex>philosophy</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Reasoning; argumentation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of good and evil much they argued then, . . . ⟦br⟧
Vain wisdom all, and false <qex>philosophy</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The course of sciences read in the schools.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A treatise on philosophy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Philosophy of the Academy</b></col>, <cd>that of Plato,
who taught his disciples in a grove in Athens called the Academy.</cd>
-- <col><b>Philosophy of the Garden</b></col>, <cd>that of Epicurus, who
taught in a garden in Athens.</cd> -- <col><b>Philosophy of the
Lyceum</b></col>, <cd>that of Aristotle, the founder of the Peripatetic
school, who delivered his lectures in the Lyceum at Athens.</cd> --
<col><b>Philosophy of the Porch</b></col>, <cd>that of Zeno and the
Stoics; -- so called because Zeno of Citium and his successors taught in
the porch of the Poicile, a great hall in Athens.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Philostorgy</ent>⟦br⟧
